actual_log_kpi = log1p(626807) ≈ 13.35
predicted_log_kpi ≈ intercept + small GQV contribution (likely much lower than 13.35)
residual = actual - predicted → large positive value
residual_z = (residual - resid_mean) / resid_std = 4.74 → exceeds RED threshold (4.0)
Why this is a false positive:
The ridge regression model learns: "higher spend → higher KPI". When ALL spend is zero, the model predicts a low KPI. But in reality, sales can be significant even without recorded media spend (organic demand, brand equity, etc.). The large residual (z=4.74) reflects the model's inability to predict zero-spend scenarios, not an actual behavior break.

A KPI "behavior break" is supposed to detect when the relationship between spend and KPI shifts. When there's no spend at all, there's no meaningful relationship to evaluate -- the residual is noise, not signal.

Additional issue: "Promo_flag" and "In_stock_Rate" are excluded from the model
The schema inference ignores:

In_stock_Rate -- a clearly important predictor for retail sales, but not in KNOWN_CONTROL_COLS
Promo_flag -- promotional context (text column, not binary)
This makes the model weaker, amplifying residuals.

Recommended fix:
In detect_kpi_behavior_break, skip detection when the latest row's total spend is zero or near-zero. The model has no predictive signal in this scenario:

